From f081265f204f14af2f18f5b647da7540242885fe Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@ik.me>
Date: Thu, 7 May 2026 23:18:58 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 098/174] mm/ioremap: generic_ioremap_prot aligns by
 MMUPAGE_SIZE
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

generic_ioremap_prot trimmed phys_addr down to PAGE_MASK and inflated
size with PAGE_ALIGN.  Page tables walk at MMUPAGE (hardware page)
granularity, so under page-clustering the rounding is excessive — a
typical 0x200-byte virtio-mmio MMIO region got rounded up to PAGE_SIZE
which at PGCL=6 (4K MMU) is 256KB.

Two consequences:
1. The vmap area is inflated PAGE_MMUCOUNT× (256KB instead of 4KB) per
   ioremap, wasting kernel virtual address space.
2. The mapping covers a region that crosses well past the device's
   actual MMIO boundary.  On QEMU virt aarch64 the virtio-mmio bank
   spans only 0xA000000-0xA003FFF (32 devices × 0x200), so a 256KB
   mapping starting at 0xA000000 reaches into 0xA040000 which is
   unmapped bus space.  An ioremap of device 1 (offset 0x200) shifts
   phys_addr down to 0xA000000 and inflates size to 256KB, mapping
   the same overlap.  The first read inside virtio_mmio_probe at
   vm_dev->base + VIRTIO_MMIO_MAGIC_VALUE then takes a synchronous
   external abort (ESR=0x96000010), pre-fix.

Switch the rounding and iounmap's vaddr calculation to MMUPAGE_SIZE/
MMUPAGE_MASK.  On non-PGCL builds MMUPAGE_SIZE == PAGE_SIZE so behavior
is identical.

Verified: aarch64 PGCL=6 standalone boot now progresses past
virtio_mmio_probe through PCI enumeration, virtio-pci enable, the
serial driver init, megasas, physmap-flash setup — next blocker is a
hang during physmap-flash MTD probe (likely another large-mapping
issue, separate follow-up).

Signed-off-by: Nadia Chambers <nadia.yvette.chambers@gmail.com>

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 mm/ioremap.c | 15 +++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/mm/ioremap.c b/mm/ioremap.c
index c36dd9f62fd5..2d574494e49f 100644
--- a/mm/ioremap.c
+++ b/mm/ioremap.c
@@ -28,10 +28,17 @@ void __iomem *generic_ioremap_prot(phys_addr_t phys_addr, size_t size,
 	if (!size || last_addr < phys_addr)
 		return NULL;
 
-	/* Page-align mappings */
-	offset = phys_addr & (~PAGE_MASK);
+	/*
+	 * MMUPAGE-align mappings.  Page tables walk at MMUPAGE granularity
+	 * regardless of page-clustering; aligning by PAGE_SIZE inflates the
+	 * vmap area by PAGE_MMUCOUNT× (e.g. 256KB at PGCL=6) for tiny MMIO
+	 * regions like a 0x200-byte virtio-mmio device, and rounds the
+	 * mapping out into adjacent unrelated physical addresses that a
+	 * later access can stray into.
+	 */
+	offset = phys_addr & (~MMUPAGE_MASK);
 	phys_addr -= offset;
-	size = PAGE_ALIGN(size + offset);
+	size = ALIGN(size + offset, MMUPAGE_SIZE);
 
 	area = __get_vm_area_caller(size, VM_IOREMAP, IOREMAP_START,
 				    IOREMAP_END, __builtin_return_address(0));
@@ -59,7 +66,7 @@ EXPORT_SYMBOL(ioremap_prot);
 
 void generic_iounmap(volatile void __iomem *addr)
 {
-	void *vaddr = (void *)((unsigned long)addr & PAGE_MASK);
+	void *vaddr = (void *)((unsigned long)addr & MMUPAGE_MASK);
 
 	if (is_ioremap_addr(vaddr))
 		vunmap(vaddr);
